at the occasion of international women's rights day,  another very interesting french talk will be organised at @alliancefrancaisekl !
â¬‡ more info and rsvp â¬‡
.
.

â€¢ â€¢ â€¢ â€¢ â€¢
this month we will have the pleasure of hosting a discussion on the issue of women's rights between rozana isa, executive director of sister in islam forum, and anne-cÃ©cile mailfert, founder of the french foundation "fondation des femmes". this french talk will be moderated by kartini ariffin, former host of 3r (respek, relaks, respon) who has spearheaded numerous digital media projects in the area of young women empowerment.
the speakers, both experienced activists, will share their experiences in advocating women's rights in malaysia and france and reflect on the way ahead for us: what methods can be used most effectively to advocate women's rights today? in the light of the recent #metoo movement and its ripples worldwide, to what extent are women's rights to be understood universally or adapted to specific cultural contexts? how much progress still needs to be done to ensure equal rights between men and women ?

rsvp at www.alliancefrancaise.org.my

organised by
embassy of france in malaysia
alliance franÃ§aise de kuala lumpur ------------------------------------------------------- what is french talks?

welcoming french and malaysian experts, it aims at creating a space of dialogue, and a bridge between the two countries and their cultures. this is particularly timely in this new malaysia where people are willing to express their views

text:
r. kelly, one of the most successful r&b acts of all time, was still in jail sunday afternoon after he failed to immediately produce the $100,000 in cash required to make bail
.
a judge in chicago set kelly's total bond at $1 million on saturday, a day after he was indicted on 10 counts of aggravated sexual abuse against four victims, three of whom would have been underage at the time of the alleged crimes, according to prosecutors
.
kelly's bond was set at $250,000 for each of the alleged victims in the case. to leave police custody, he's required to pay 10% of the total, or $100,000. steve greenberg
.
but greenberg said his client "really doesn't have any money at this point" due to "mismanagement," "hangers-on" and "bad deals." he added kelly would ultimately be able to come up with the required $100,000. "he's trying to get it together," greenberg said. "he doesn't have it sitting in the bank." illinois does not have bail bondsmen, greenberg pointed out
.
also according to court documents, kelly owed more than $169,000 in unpaid child support to his ex-wife as of february 6. the court ordered kelly to make a monthly payment of $20,833 on january 8, 2009, but kelly failed to show up to that hearing, per court documents. to avoid being held in contempt of court, a judge ordered he pay $161,663 by march 6
.
greenberg told cnn his client "does not have to pay the child support before getting out." "the state is trying to make him do that, or they were," greenberg said, "but the judge said no." kelly also risked eviction at his chicago studio last month because he owes more than $166,000 in unpaid rent
.
court documents show a judge signed an eviction order in january. the documents show robert kelly needed to move out on or before january 21, but kelly was still at the studio minutes before he turned himself in to police on friday.
.

room full of people and i will be able to tell my story, my side of what happened.. how  scared, alone and weak you've made me feel. in 7 hours i go on that stand not only for me but for every girl that you've ever made feel uncomfortable, for every girl you've tried to take advantage of. i'm going in that court room not just for me.. but for a world of women that cant or wont speak up for whatever reason. but you know what... in approximately 10 hours i will move on and try to put it past me because no matter what you've done to me you will not break me and i will come out of this stronger. #metoomovement #growingstronger #sexualassault #survivor #metoo #nomeansno

text:
it is a tired morning, but a full morning, in large part due to the work, but in larger part because these days are cantilevered on all sides by human beings that support me unconditionally, who will and do rally behind me at all times, pushing me up on all sides reminding me to be my best self without apology or explanation. & so i do, and this space is where the world opens up to you, where you and your life are free-flowing and kind; you see the world reflected back at you with a certain quality of absoluteness on the one hand, and on the other it is not about reality but about your trust in your own ability to render realityâ€”or some resonant aspects of itâ€”exquisitely, and this is where the magic lives: in feeling, in intuition alone. the only word that matters is the one that makes someone feel something.
.
.
.
the hustle ain't easy, but i love it. here for the real shit, married to the game. #cantstopwontstop

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.
http://www.almahdyoon.org
#women_in_the_divine_governmen

in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

fixed it!  so from a legal and human rights perspective, my version is more accurate.  how on earth, then, do we have it so reversed??
.
for one, patients, providers, and the public are unaware of the rights of birthing people.  yes, all three of those groups.  most people believe that the doctor "ultimately" has the right to make decisions about birth.
.
obviously, this contributes to a lot of problems: skyrocketing induction and c-section rates, birth trauma and ptsd, and yeah, i'll say it--even more reinforcement of truly messed up cultural beliefs and norms around how women and mothers are valued.  which is to say, not very much.  the birth room is where prejudice, sexism, racism, classism, and all kinds of other -isms converge on individuals at their absolute most vulnerable.
.
how do we flip that on its head?  we start with education.  i'll tell you what, it pissed me off when i found out after the fact that i had always had the right to say "no" to an induction being pushed on me.  i always thought i would have advocated for myself that much more confidently if i had known just how strong my rights were and what they were based on.
.
doulas and birth workers: you are the front line for this kind of education.  if you took my class, you'd understand why i feel so confident saying: "hospital policies are really preferences.  birth plans are really policies." (p.s. i tag acog in most of these posts, just in case anyoneâ€™s listening.)
.
tonight is the last night to get this class at a great intro price--over 25% off.  you have until midnight.  so get on it!  bit.ly/birth-rights
.

text_retweet:
repost from @themysticforce
as a glistening foetus, 
uterus walls sang him lullaby of
a certain him abducting and 
another him rescuing a her
and of a her's dignity
measured in six yards. 
in second standard, 
thomas brought for him light. 
but only at matriculation, 
he learnt of currie, the 
cure to thomas's failure. 
seventh grade recited 
about young jalaluddin to him
and lessons on bakarwals 
helped him with geopolitics
of kathua. 
as adolescence assumed, 
homogeneity of flesh
ripe with facts and fiction
of puckish prejudice, 
pronged into a two tined fork
cleansing it was sister's task
and clanging nailheads, his. 
stifling below the rubble 
of this oblivious obviousness
became everyday, 
a slight stumble here, 
lifting extra kilos 
with pretentious ease
and a little gulp there
of tears and fears. 
until he was 
scrambled and screwed
like eggs and in orifices
pinched and ravished
at his sense and skeleton. 
failing the experiment
of mutating men for robots and
falling off while escalating stairs
of executing expectations. 
stuffed till brim
with generalisation 
and genderization, 
he couldn't take 
the leap of faith
so, he took to the loop. 
suicide shouted 
what masculinity feared, 
rape. .- @themysticforce

text:
i had a close friend tell me one day that, "people that have a  personality like yours connor usually have had something major happen to them." this is my choice to tell my story.  when i was around 8 living in springville i made a new friend.  this "new friend" i made actually turned out to be my rapist.  i was raped i believe to be 3 times.  this put me into long years of anxiety and depression.  i've only told close friends not any family members, due to the fact, a lot are very lds and i dont wanna receive criticism, but i'm 19 and have made the decision to put my story out there.  this changed my life forever.  don't think of me any different.  i am the same person you all know me to be.  thanks.
#sexualassault #life #tellafriend #dontbeafraid #sameoldme #utah #lds #mormon #anxiety #metoo

text:
ğŸ’¥warning::: this is deep and could be triggering. talk of sexual abuse. .  this is not about anyone from my recent history. this happened over 5 years ago
.
.
â€œi am ready to accept that i am not ready, and to fight anyway.â€
.
.
.
i have come a long way. a very long way from the scared, self conscious girl i use to be. i have overcome obstacles of doubt, self hate, fear of being unloved, not being good enough, addiction, eating disorders, abuse.... oh god, the fucking abuse.
.
.
it took me years to accept that i had been both sexually and mentally abused. two separate relationships both gone wrong. when youâ€™re in it, really fucking in it, you canâ€™t see it. i thought, â€œoh i deserve thisâ€.... itâ€™s my fault that iâ€™m being told how disgusting my body looks. or that iâ€™m being held down fighting to not look like iâ€™m terrified of whatâ€™s coming. i thought, oh this is normal. he thinks this is okay.... or she wouldnâ€™t hurt me, she loves me..... i thought being strong meant being able to endure the pain. .
.
.
there are people who show up in our lives to teach us things. teach us how strong we really are. i am grateful for all of the people that have surrounded me and shown me true love over the past several years. the people that stuck with me knowing i had scars without really knowing how deep they ran. the people that love me despite how much i wasnâ€™t ready to love myself. .
.
it wasnâ€™t easy. no one likes to tell you how painful it is to heal but when you make it through the mess, it is the most beautiful feeling in the world. now i am alive. i am confident and empowered by my soul and my body. i love myself so much more than anyone else could love me. and this is only the beginning. .
.
my purpose in life is to help others know and see their worth and to love themselves as fully as possible. let me be your light. let me hold space to love you even if you donâ€™t love yourself right now. you are an incredible light to the world and it is time to shine. there is never a right time to start your healing journey. so let me be there with you as you take the first step. .
.
my heart is with you my loves. .
.
.

text:
even from jail, sex abuser manipulated the system. his victims were kept in the dark

a decade before #metoo, a multimillionaire sex offender from florida got the ultimate break.

palm beach county courthouse

june 30, 2008

jeffrey edward epstein appeared at his sentencing dressed comfortably in a blue blazer, blue shirt, jeans and gray sneakers. his attorney, jack goldberger, was at his side.

at the end of the 68-minute hearing, the 55-year-old silver-haired financier â€” accused of sexually abusing dozens of underage girls â€” was fingerprinted and handcuffed, just like any other criminal sentenced in florida.

but inmate no. w35755 would not be treated like other convicted sex offenders in the state of florida, which has some of the strictest sex offender laws in the nation.

ten years before the #metoo movement raised awareness about the kid-glove handling of powerful men accused of sexual abuse,Â epsteinâ€™s lenient sentence and his extraordinary treatmentwhile in custody are still the source of consternation for the victims he was accused of molesting when they were minors.

beginning as far back as 2001,Â epstein lured a steady stream of underage girls to his palm beach mansionÂ to engage in nude massages, masturbation, oral sex and intercourse, court and police records show. the girls â€” mostly from disadvantaged, troubled families â€” were recruited from middle and high schools around palm beach county. epstein would pay the girls for massages and offer them further money to bring him new girls every time he was at his home in palm beach, according to police reports.

the girls, now in their late 20s and early 30s, allege in a series of federal civil lawsuits filed over the past decade that epstein sexually abused hundreds of girls, not only in palm beach, but at his homes in manhattan, new mexico and in the caribbean.

in 2007, the fbi had prepared a 53-page federal indictment charging epstein with sex crimes that could have put him in federal prison for life. but then-miami u.s. attorneyÂ alexander acosta signed off on a non-prosecution agreement, which was negotiated, signed and sealed so that no one would know the full scope ...

text:
after thousands of its employeesÂ walked out in protest last novemberÂ over the handling of handling #sexualharassment cases, #google has announced it will drop forced arbitration requirements for all of its staff.

the common business practice requires workers to take legal disputes to private arbitration â€“ where there is no judge or jury. in this process they are less likely to win their cases and if they do are likely to get less compensation that a court would grant.

it sparked outrage after it was revealed thatÂ android founder andy rubin was allowed to exit with a packageÂ worth tens of millions of dollars in the wake of sexual harassment allegations by employees - which he denied.

activists led a protest in november, which was backed by thousands of google staffers, which listed six demands. in addition to the end of forced arbitration, they wants a commitment to end pay and opportunity inequality and the creation of a sexual harassment transparency report.

now, from 21 march, both existing and new employees at google will have the option to sue in court and to join together in class-action #lawsuits.

to learn more visit legalactionnews.com

text: being a woman is no easy feat. i was 7 when a boy told me to go into his closet for a surprise and made me kiss him. i was 14 when a junior at my high school put his hands under my shirt and told me to let it happen. i was 15 when my teacher said it was a good thing i was pretty because i wasnâ€™t smart enough to go to college. i was 20 when i was sexually assaulted and was told by the police not to bother reporting it because it would â€œbe too hard for meâ€. i was 23 when i was told by a corporate officer after an investigation into my report of sexual misconduct that my personality was â€œtoo outgoingâ€ which is why this man corned me in an elevator and forced himself on me, prompting her to ask me if â€œi learned anything from this incidentâ€. i was 24 when a supervisor started to make inappropriate comments towards me, and when i reported this to my manager i was told he has two kids to support and to â€œlet it goâ€. i was 26 when i told him no, but he forced me anyway. i was 29 when i stopped lying about why i left arizona. i was 29 when i finally told my family about my assault. i was 29 when i became an advocate for myself. i was 29 when i cut out toxic people from my life. i was 29 when i decided enough was enough and take a stand against sexism and push the envelope. iâ€™m 4 months away from 30. letâ€™s see what else i can do #metoo #timesup #believesurvivors #womensreality #everydaysexism

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.
http://www.almahdyoon.org

.
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
at night,
when the birds sleep and
the moon hides,
your hands begin to slide.
over my curves
until they reach
for what they hunger.
and then you rub.
hoping to create some kind of desire,
attempting to stir me from my slumber.
.
i used to not fight it,
thinking it was me
who started all of this.
it had to be.
youâ€”you wouldnâ€™t do this to me,
when you knew of my past.
you wouldnâ€™t take this,
not...
.
so, there we were,
fucking beneath the starless night,
until you were satisfied
and i was left huddled on my side.
youâ€™d cage your arms around me,
dragging me back to your chest,
whispering you loved me.
but no one ever told you,
that it isnâ€™t love if in the end
your lover wants to fly away.
.
far, far away,
to where stars shine,
to where kind men reside,
to where safe hands will catch her,
to where she can finally feel the sunlight.
.
and as you slept,
as i silently cried,
i begged for the moon

again

donâ€™t know a damn thing

the moon hides,
your hands begin to slide.
over my curves
until they reach
for what they hunger.
and then you rub.
hoping to create some kind of desire,
attempting to stir me from my slumber.

thinking it was me
who started all of this.
it had to be.
youâ€”you wouldnâ€™t do this to me,
when you knew of my past.
you wouldnâ€™t take this,
not...
.

fucking beneath the starless night,
until you were satisfied
and i was left huddled on my side.
youâ€™d cage your arms around me,
dragging me back to your chest,
whispering you loved me.

your lover wants to fly away.

neurology retraction for 'racist characterizations'â£â €
â£â €
an editor of neurology, the flagship journal of the aan, has resigned following the swift retraction last week of an article because it contained what the editor admitted were "racist characterizations."â£â €
â£â €
"the error has compelled us to seriously re-examine our editorial processes, informed by conversations with a number of diversity leaders within the aan," editor-in chief robert a. gross, md, wrote. â£â €
â£â €
as medscape medical news previously reported, the now-retracted essay, "lucky and the root doctor," described "reggie, a 60-year-old black man referred because of muscle weakness and suspected inflammatory myopathy." â£â €
â£â €
it said that reggie's wife was "a roly-poly woman" whose "abundant rolls of fat jiggled as she giggled."â£â €
â£â €
the author of the article, william w. campbell, md, msha, an emeritus professor at the uniformed services university of health sciences and a retired colonel in the us army, told medscape medical news last week that he did not mean to offend anyone.â£â €
â£â €
in addition to immediately suspending the journal's humanities section, the publication "will require that any paper that focuses on a group of people (for example, racial treatment disparities in stroke care) will have a member of that group, or a content expert on that group, or both, who will assure that the handling editor will have an appropriate range of opinion on which to base decisions..."â£â €
â£â €

#
after the red carpet statement of last yearâ€™s awards season, which saw a-listers strut their stuff in somber black at the golden globes and suffragette white at the oscars, the gowns came off - and so did the gloves. the raised voices of the entitled stars of hollywood did not only encourage the war cries of women from other areas to ring out and ring true with women across the globe, but it forced men to expect it and normalise it. how the men reacted after this was up to them, we made them aware, and we could now judge them accordingly - in the workplace, as co-parents, in the media. if sweet, soft, southern reese witherspoon could make a stand, telling the world â€œi can feel a reckoningâ€ regarding the picking up of pace regarding womenâ€™s time to be heard with her support of the #metoo and #timesup movements, we can too. still, has anything really changed in the last 12 months in hollywood? we can all thrill in the triumvirate of glorious actresses in the favorite or - at last! - the sharing of the secret pain of women in domestic work in roma. but not one femaleâ€¦

text:
20 weeks out vs 20 weeks out
i really wanted to do a comparison of my last off season end point vs this off season end point because there really are some serious changes that have occurred.
_
left: 129.5 lbs, less confident going into the season, off season was hit really hard with mental health (#metoo), just came off a 3 week flu, trained average 4 days a week
right: 125.5 lbs, more confident going into the season, kept level headed through off season, got sick and car accident so missed a couple weeks of training in the middle, trained average 4.5 days a week
_
if i ended up where i ended up last year with that as a starting point and 26 weeks of prep, i cannot wait to see what i can do this year with 20 to my first show and 23 to my second!

.
â€œi am ready to accept that i am not ready, and to fight anyway.â€
.
i have come a long way. a very long way from the scared, self conscious girl i use to be. i have overcome obstacles of doubt, self hate, fear of being unloved, not being good enough, addiction, eating disorders, abuse.... oh god, the fucking abuse.
.
.
it took me years to accept that i had been both sexually and mentally abused. two separate relationships both gone wrong. when youâ€™re in it, really fucking in it, you canâ€™t see it. i thought, â€œoh i deserve thisâ€.... itâ€™s my fault that iâ€™m being told how disgusting my body looks. or that iâ€™m being held down fighting to not look like iâ€™m terrified of whatâ€™s coming. i thought, oh this is normal. he thinks this is okay.... or she wouldnâ€™t hurt me, she loves me..... i thought being strong meant being able to endure the pain.
.
.
.
there are people who show up in our lives to teach us things. teach us how strong we really are. i am grateful for all of the people that have surrounded me and shown me true love over the past several years. the people that stuck with me knowing i had scars without really knowing how deep they ran. the people that love me despite how much i wasnâ€™t ready to love myself. .
.

.

.
my heart is with you my loves. .
.
.

text: when something hurts our feelings today, it is triggering a wound from a long time ago. we tend to blame the present moment situation, but in reality we are re-feeling something that happened to us in our childhood. this is good news! we can be loving toward that younger part of ourselves and send a ton of love to that little one inside of us. in this way, we can rewire our brain circuitry and reparent ourselves in order to feel more love, compassion, and soothing in our lives.
name: A Brave New Man Podcast

i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). text:
a few years back i got deeper into my health journey and learned of the dangers hidden in store brand feminine products. i wanted to do something about it but didn't know what. then someone shared a video about some dope ass pads. i had to be down. my cramps were horrible, i had to double up with a pad and tampon on day 1 & 2 and i was flying through the pack because i couldn't stand sitting in moisture. my cycle ran for 7-8 days.  it was uncomfortable...and i ain't like that sh$@.
.
. 
but after seeing the video (oh trust me stay tuned cuz i'm posting it ğŸ˜) and getting my 1st pack...and applying my 1st pad i haven't looked back. .

my cramps we're gone within an hour... .

i no longer had to double up (absorbency waaay better than the leading pad).... .

i don't even finish the pack by the end... .

that 7 day tryst... down to barely a panty liners at day 4 0_o .

i believe in these pads man...they worked so well for me that i was driven to educate and introduce women to a healthier way. and on top of that pack some natural, organic, handmade goodies to enable you to have a happy period. there are many  boxes out here and i can promise the absolute real with no frills. only a few items you will see in the box that you can get just anywhere. everything else has been researched, acquired and tried by me. meaning i got it used...and went oooooh it's going in. .
.  let's do this. link the bio. subscription levels coming soon.
. *results vary woman to woman... the testimonial was 100% my experience.*

text:
chloÃ¨ (@chloescorouches) on rejection and fear. âœ¨ğŸ¦‹
â€”
â€œseeing rejection as redirection is always something people preach about and encourage others to do, but truthfully, itâ€™s something you really have to experience for yourself to really be able to understand. 
i have been out of college for a while, for financial and health reasons and to say it has been difficult would be a definite understatement. i started university in the us at 17, moving there by myself - no family, no friends, i had been to the us many times prior to that, but living there full time & being there in such a capacity was a totally new experience for me. this was something i had to figure out on my own and really quickly, life hit really hard and fast, and it just kept hitting after i stopped college.

not being in college right now, made me realize i really didnâ€™t know me. while not having a solid plan and a clear sense of â€œpurpose", iâ€™ve come realize thereâ€™s much more to life than that. iâ€™ve been blogging my journey since then and while i canâ€™t say iâ€™ve found myself, iâ€™ve come out of my comfort zone - i donâ€™t think people really understand just how hard it is to post on the internet/youtube, especially for a sheltered introvert.

i can definitely say i learn more and more about myself every day, and thatâ€™s something iâ€™ve yearned for since high school. sometimes it really takes losing everything (even though no-one ever wants to lose) to realize what really matters.  fear? we do not know her. even at your weakest, still leave 'em speechless.â€ #ourwomensvoices #blackhistorymonth

this quotation is from one of my favorite pieces of literature. it belongs to women who run with wolves by clarissa pinkola estÃ©s.
.
clarissa writes about what it means to me a womxn from a mythological and embodied perspectives. diving deeply into the shadow sides of the psyche while being potent and specific with emphasized compassion to illicit more consciousness to the unconscious portions of all humans. .
there is not a more beautifully written book that both exposes our suffering and how we perpetuate to it ourselves with such grace. .
i was gifted clarissa's book years ago while attending treatment for my eating disorder. at the time i did not know how a book of myths and fairy tales could possibly provide any healing. i was dominated by the masculine and rejecting of anything feminine. this included clarissa's book.
.
it would take months after being gifted the book by a naturopathic doctor for me to open the pages and dive deeply in. .
once i did, once i began reading, once i put my masculine aside... i found shadow aspects of myself contained in each of the stories. parts of me that had been pushed had representation in clarissa's written words.
.
these parts of myself no longer felt denied and ignored they felt liberated by finally having something to identify with.
.
and it was through identification that these parts of myself where able to bloom from the cocoon of my unconscious mind into their full totality.

 hollywood's biggest night took time to deliver a timely message and celebrate diversity in filmmaking; 
ashley judd, salma hayek and annabella sciorra â€” three women who publicly accused harvey weinstein of sexual misconduct â€” took the stage together to introduce the segment.

when jimmy kimmel kicked off this year's oscars, he promised a light of positivity" during his opening monologue. during the third act of sunday's show, that promise materialized when the academy devoted a segment to honoring the  and time's up movements and highlighted the diversity in movie-making in the last year. "many spoke their truth and the journey ahead is long, but slowly a new path has emerged," said judd, referencing the women and men who have come forward to say  and time's up. those voices have joined together to create a "mighty chorus," she added. judd shared a hope that the next 90 years of the academy awards will "empower these limitless possibilities of equality, diversity inclusivity, intersectionality â€” that's what this year has promised us." hayek then introduced a pre-taped segment highlighting some of this year's most diverse and ground-breaking filmmakers â€” from greta gerwig and dee rees to  duvernay and kumail jiani â€” whom she referred to as "unstoppable spirits who kicked ass and broke through bias perceptions against their gender racer and ethnicity to tell their stories." jimmy kimmel said "we need to set an example and if we can work together here to stop sexual harassment in the workplace, women will only have to deal with harassment all the time, at every other place they go." perhaps speaking to critics of hollywood award shows who believe they have grown "too political," kimmel explained that the night's show would include brave and outspoken voices of the   and  movements in hopes of spurring positive change. "this is a night for positivity," he declared before rattling off all the names of nominees who had the potential to break or set new records if they were to win.

text:
this is an interesting video, i just wanted to give me opinion on the statements said in this video. 1) i actually don't know how to change a tire but i would like to learn. 
2) boys and girls should be raised the same way. in my opinion i don't think so, boys and girls act very different from each other and raising them the same way won't change anything. the outcome is more likely going to be the same. boys are biologically stronger than girls anyway.
3) every woman should be a feminist. no, being a feminist has different meaning to everyone and if a woman doesn't want to identify as one she shouldn't have too or be told she should.
4) i believe abortion should be legal. yes but it should have trigger laws. late term abortions are a no no, having one with a good reason like rape/ incest (even though it's like 1.5% of abortions occur because of that.) is ok. doing it because you can't financially support the baby is dumb, because everyone who is old enough to have sexual intercourse knows that you can get pregnant that way and that safe sex doesn't always work.
5) i don't mind stranger flirting with me. i honestly don't care, if it happens it happens. 
6) i support the #metoo movement. it's ideally a good cause but i don't think it'll stop sexual harrassment, assault and excludes men even though it happens to them too.
7) i believe the world would be better if it run by women. absolutely not..
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#politics #politicalpost #feminist #political

text:
whatâ€™s a predator? .
a predator, is opportunistic. a predator, will sniff out an opportunity with a goal to take advantage of a person or situation.  as hunters, they study their subject with laser precision and why itâ€™s important for those who are still in the struggle of abuse, or coming out the storm and currently safe to begin to train for those â€œtestâ€ by learning how to set boundaries. .
.
i remember walking my journey to freedom like it was yesterday.  it was so important for me to take time, and go on a journey of self-love by any means necessary.  i felt as if one understood my pain not from the bruises, but from the emotional damage that was worse than any bruise i can remember. .
.
my insecurities shined bright which translates to being vulnerable to predators.  i had to dig deep, and ask myself the hard questions with a goal to find the core reason i allowed  someone else to set my value in the world. .
.
i did not know what i wanted, who i wanted to become, or how i was going to break the chains of abuse i had known for so long. 
the only thing i knew was, i deserved more. 
with a safety-plan in place, i left everything i owned, to invest in myself. 
ladies, gentlemen, sisters, and brothers, i encourage you to think about a safety plan to leave, or a plan to get unstuck after abuse. .
.
please know the journey is necessary to dig deep, take the route thatâ€™s most challenging for you to get back to, you!  be resolute in owning them and set your boundaries.

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
i've finally decided to talk about what happened to me in november of 2017.

i was visiting a cousin in edinburgh. i'd went to a club for the first time. i was staying sober that night and had no plans to drink anything. my cousin headed straight for a fog filled dance floor. i stayed at the edge away from the floor in a reasonably dark quiet spot. i was almost enjoying it when a much older woman walked up to me. she was taller and at least double my age, being 18 at the time. she eyed me up and down, then after a second reached over and grabbed my balls. she then looked me dead in the eye with a smile and leaned in and said something to me. i honestly don't remember what she said but she thought it was amusing as she chuckled. her friend then walked up and dragged her off to the fog of the dance floor without a word or second look.

i left immediately and headed straight for the student digs i was crashing at and walked 3 miles alone in the dark and cold.

i then proceeded to drink every drop of alcohol on the digs. and did my best to black out the memory.

no more

i'm not gonna pretend it didn't happen. i'm not gonna pretend what happened wasn't assault. i'm not gonna pretend it's not the reason i refuse to go near clubs. i'm not gonna be silenced. i'm not gonna listen to you tell me i'm lucky that it happened to me as i was told by other people i've told.

assault doesn't have a gender.

#metoo

.â €

.â €

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
in the same way malcolm talks of allah putting people and situations in his path at the right time, i honestly believe this book came in to my life at the perfect time. i know that i wouldnâ€™t have been able to draw the same parallels with the world we live in today nor would his unwavering pride to be black and muslim in a structurally racist society set a fire in me as it does today.

at so many points i had to look back and check what year these interviews took place in - the overwhelming and crushing reality of reading his words, is how between now and then, nothing has changed. underneath all the decorum, doctrines, laws and loopholes, racism still thrives with the same ferocity as it did then but cloaked in layers of doubt and uncertainty today - which he forecasts anyway. i love how fluid and vibrant the writing is describing his life as a hustler in harlem - a system and a culture he didnâ€™t grow up in, but understood. that same language allowed him to tap into the minds of thousands of young black men in the same way no one else could, and ultimately why he was killed. the way he talks about islam during hajj is approached with such a beautiful tenderness and humility - an almost childlike adoration and fascination, a rebirth into the beauty of islam, the oneness of mankind and the oneness of god. 
i wonâ€™t lie, i felt truly uncomfortable reading his views on women - but after reading several essays i understand that they were his views under the nation of islam and elijah muhammad - already flawed on so many levels, and no different on women. his views had changed later on in his life and he was assassinated before he could view the final draft of his autobiography and rectify those opinions. i loved speaking to @zainoted about this - she sent me one of her tweets saying that we should not forget that he was ready to die to go against the teachings of elijah, a known misogynist - linking it to todayâ€™s #metoo movement... (read the rest in comments!)

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
by: @artistic_tomato "what i am trying to depict in this artwork is that innocent men are blamed for being men and many feminists (not all) label them as â€œtoxicâ€. -
today, feminism is a huge movement. itâ€™s aim is to make women and men equal. i am completely for feminism, and i think it is for a good cause. however, many so-called â€œfeministsâ€ attempt to bring men down as a way to bring themselves up; they often accuse all men of being bad. a couple weeks ago, a gillette ad practically accused all men of being sexual predators (in the ad, they repeatedly said â€œboys will be boysâ€ and proceeded to show men assaulting women). lately, many feminists have labeled men as toxic and violent and have coined the phrase â€œtoxic masculinityâ€. itâ€™s unfair to assume that all men are â€œtoxicâ€ and that being masculine makes you violent or a rapist. 
we should not generalize groups of people. not all men are rapists and not all women are innocent.
i hope that we not only establish equality for all but that we also reduce the double standards in todayâ€™s society. men donâ€™t rape people. rapists rape people, and we should work on fighting against this problem."
name: Masculinist | Meninist

â£ â™¥ï¸â£
do not judge the bereaved mother.
she comes in many forms.
she is breathing, but she is dying.
she may look young, but inside she has become ancient.
she smiles, but her heart sobs.
she walks, she talks, she cooks,
she cleans, she works, she is
but she is not all at once.
she is here, but part of her is elsewhere for eternity.
a child that loses a parent is an orphan.
a husband that loses his wife is a widower.
a wife who loses her husband is a widow.
however, there is no word for a parent that loses a child.
for there is no word to describe such pain.

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.
http://www.almahdyoon.org
#women_in_the_divine_governmen

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
â€œitâ€™s been a rough day, i just need a drinkâ€

what is your choice of comfort? 
is it wine?
whiskey? 
chocolate? 
food?
pills? 
social hour? 
a go to person/lover/friend? 
what is the first thing you want to do when life gets tough?? you see we all have a vice! 
we all have our preferable way to band aid our problems. 
whatever it is, food or drink. 
the comfort we are finding in these things, are temporary. 
they are a bandaid to an unstoppable bleed. 
the truth is, turning to food and drink for comfort, actually only breeds more discomfort. 
discomfort in our waistline, our mind, our clarity, our healing. 
we prolong working through, and healing when we never run to the actual healer and comforter. 
when we are turning to our fork and knife to comfort, we actually are serving more than our food.  we are severing the ability to find true wholeness in our comforter. 
our fork and knife could be the very thing dividing us from seeking and receiving gods true freedom, healing and blessing. ----------------- going through my divorce i decided from day 1, i would not turn to bandaids. 
i would not turn to false comforts. 
i gave up comfort eating, i gave up any consumption of alcohol, certain relationships, tv shows... and honestly it was not all that comfortable in the process!!! however, 
i decided to live, sleep, eat, breathe 
all things life giving 
activities, and relationships. 
if you find yourself running to â€œthingsâ€ for comfort instead of the comforter, 
i want to invite you into a new season of life giving activities with me! â€¢
join me on a spiritual, mental and physical health quest this march!

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.
http://www.almahdyoon.org
#women_in_the_divine_governmen

text:
this afternoon i ran into chef antonuela ariza, adorned with a tote bag of fresh produce from the local sunday farmerâ€™s market and accompanied by two american friends from slow food. ğŸŒ¿ .

out of all the women i have met in my three weeks in bogota, she has been the one to set the greatest impression of the city. as a mother and the co-founder/co-chef of mini-mal (arguably the restaurant to start the farm-to-table movement in bogota back in 2001), i am not surprised to find antonuela on the cityâ€™s official day of family-time and rest, showing two visitors around. her heart is bigger than i even thought possible and i get the impression it guides every decision she makes. i now understand why mini-mal has become such a success. despite her busy schedule, she made the time to meet me for lunch and i just had to capture her beauty in the dreamy light of mesa franca. thank you antonuela for giving me a much-needed dose of inspiration.

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
i invite all readers to peruse seyed ahmad alhassan's explanation of this subject thouthfully and deeply, because he has responded to all the controversies surrounding the issue of the polygamy of the messenger of allah (pbuh).
in this regard,  he(pbuh) stated that: "but the issue of marriage at the time of the messenger of allah, mohammad (pbuh), and especially in the conditions of his life, even before islam, there were also numerous marriages, because of the increasing proportion of women to #men , and as it is clear that in order to solve this problem, there was  no acceptable social solution except polygamy. 
the reason why there was such a problem at that time was that there were constant wars and raids,
and this always let lots of men to be killed; while women stayed home and did not routinely go out and no danger threatened them, they were even captured and not killed like men in the wars. 
this increase in the number of women in those living conditions was such a social problem that many women who did not find a husband would raise flags for declaring their tendency to have sex with men, and #women who had red flags were famous in the society. 
many men killed their daughters in their infancy, a phenomenon that was known as burying-girls-alive, and the cause of this phenomenon was the increase in the number of women, most of whom did not achieve husbands, in the community and tended to have sexual relationships without a social law (like marriage). (facebook official page, 23/06/2013) * read the whole article in the site.

text:
watching mommy dearest, missing my besties and my mom...it has almost been a year. fuck. i always thought i would be dead by now....so here is to being more of a fucking bad ass than i give myself credit. i had a great weekend filled with some self barriers i knocked down and let go of...i realised...nothing matters to anyone. life isnt what you have or do or sell. its not a million fans or recognition. its about being a person that the ones who do care about you deserve. if people care about you at your weakest...then they deserve for you to be your strongest for them. 
wake up. 
look in the mirror and forgive yourself. forgive those who hurt you. let go of your vices and your scars.
 the broken hearts and tragically hurtful memories. 
and say to yourself today "all of that..and i am still fucking here...no one else did this just me...and i am a bad ass!"
because it is true. 
i am a single mom of two amazing children and i have been on my own since i was 16 and never looked back. i have few friends but the ones i do have would kill for me and are always in my corner. and despite all the ugly things in this world i have seen...the abuse, the shame, the sadness, the regret and scars..the abandonment, rape, loss, fragmented memories and so much pain i thought i was made of it...i..me..endured.. and guess what..
you did too. 
and that..is pretty fucking special.

text:
southern baptists and the scandal of church sexual abuse 
this morningâ€™s edition of theÂ houston chronicleÂ features a major investigation into church sexual abuse in southern baptist contexts, looking at the harm done to over 700 survivors, including children as young as three years old. the report also details over 200 offenders who were convicted or took plea deals, demonstrating how a shocking number returned to ministry to abuse again. the report is alarming and scandalous, the courage and grace of these survivors is contrasted with the horrific depravity of those who would use the name of jesus to prey on them. so how should christians think about this latest revelation

nothing is worse than the use of the name of jesus to prey on the vulnerable

the first is to see with clear eyes what is before us.Â some have ridiculed this concern as being some irrational sweep into a secular #metoo moment, implying that the problem is â€œpolitical correctnessâ€ over an issue that is no real problem within church life. others have suggested that the church should not concern itself with questions of â€œjustice,â€ and that preaching the gospel itself will resolve matters of injustice. others have implied that the horrific scandals we have seen in the roman catholic church are due to the theology of catholicism, the nature of a celibate priesthood and so forth. all of these are not only wrongheaded responses, but are deadly dangerous both to the lives of present and future survivors of these horrors and to the witness of the church itself

be the changeğŸ‘ŠğŸ¼ğŸ‘ŠğŸ¾ğŸ‘ŠğŸ¿so hereâ€™s the thing. you can talk all kinds of amazing things about being a modern feminist, being girl positive and empowering women. i actually spend a considerable amount of time explaining what it means to be â€œfeministâ€ (which sucks) and actually having difficult conversations, with people who donâ€™t get it. itâ€™s hard for me to grasp that people still donâ€™t understand that women are not treated equally in so many areas. that being a woman for many has defaulted us into being subject to unwanted â€œsexualâ€ comments, work situations and uncomfortable positions throughout our day. 
for the longest time i didnâ€™t know this could be changed or that â€œthisâ€ uncomfortable, sometimes scary and always confusing â€œtreatmentâ€ could stop, could be changed or forced out. 
example: iâ€™m in my late 20s, i work at a senior level at a large hospital responsible for credentialing all the current physicians at the hospital, including residents and students. lots of work. lots of men.
i am almost always the only woman/girl in the room. throughout my week i have comments made about my appearance by men, comments about other women in a sexual way in front of me, my butt patted with paper as i walk by. this specific day i was on my way into the meeting room, a large room filled with mostly male physicians and the caterer who is female walks past me. as iâ€™m about to enter the room i hear a group of men discussing how â€œtheyâ€™d love to bend her overâ€ and other sexual thoughts about this poor woman, i donâ€™t even know who simply brought their god damn sandwiches. 
should i enter the room and call it out? should i make a scene? should i report it? is it worth my job? my career? 
these are the questions that come up in a day being a woman in my experience. 
it isnâ€™t easy. itâ€™s difficult and there is always something to think and stress over. 
that day may pass, but that feeling doesnâ€™t go away. it sticks and it impacts you. 
do you take the time and pressure to call out misogyny? unacceptable behaviour? do you worry about your job, career and effects of â€œstandingâ€ up to this?

text:
there is nothing i love more than teaching in person. the intensity is always that little bit extra..â£
â£
yesterdayâ€™s workshop â€œreclaiming sexyâ€ was nothing short of amazing..â£
â£
nestled in between the mountains,â£ in just over an hour i witnessed 100 women, reserved and unsure blossom open into their full power. â£
â£
i took them on a wild ride, tapping back into the power of their bodies and transcending into their most raw and primal state. unapologetic shrieks, screeches, howls, crying and screams unleashed, returning sexual trauma, pain and suffering back into the earth to be cleansed and recycled.â£
â£
they were given the opportunity in a safe, supportive space, to tap into their own innate flavour of sexy, without pressure, limitations, rules or standards and to celebrate their sexuality through movement, letting their sexual energy guide and take control instead of ego. (and boy did they take advantage of this opportunity ğŸ˜)â£
â£
at the beginning i noticed a few faces pulled like â€˜did she really just say thatâ€™ but moments later the walls came down and my stories were followed my #metoo â€˜sâ£
â£
pushing the boundaries of whatâ€™s taboo and whatâ€™s allowed to be spoken about gives other women permission to come forward and share their journey, their stories, their pain and suffering. with each story shared we realise we are a collective, we are all in this together. my pain is your pain and your pain is mine and together is the only way we can heal. supporting each other is number one!â£
â£
the workshop carried on another 2.5 hours after it officially finished. sitting around a pile of pleasure wands, all the stories came out, some of which i could tell women had been holding onto for aeons and had be craving this safe space to be seen, heard and understood. thatâ€™s my passion, no matter what workshop goes down as long as iâ€™ve created a safe space and made absolutely nothing off limits, iâ€™m happy. this is what the world needs, permission! â£
â£
feeling all the feels, and still so loved up from all the juicy hugs yesterday â¤ï¸

text:
we all know what a 'gut' feeling is... but do we know what a 'womb' feeling is?

___

did you know there was a difference?

many people think intuition, psychic gifts, gut feelings and womb feelings are all the same thing, but i'm gonna tell you right now, that they are not. yes, they are supernatural gifts of peering into the unknown, but they each have very different origins and are different types of information. each comes from a different energy center within our body for a specific purpose.

here is the breakdown:

psychic information- comes only from the 6th and 7th chakras. it is a 100% neutral level of energy which means you have no feelings attached to it. this is why psychics can come across as 'cold' or 'unfeeling'. is mostly accessed through visions and knowingness. this type of information is the best when overwhelmed with feeling and needing a neutral understanding. to access your psychic information, tune into your 6th and 7th chakras.

intuition- this is when the heart and the crown are working together at the same time to give usÂ  information. we just 'know' it to be true in our hearts. usually our heart and the top of our head feels activated. this type of information is perfect for guiding us when we don't know which way to go. to activate your intuition, tap into your heart and listen.

gut feelings- this comes from your 3rd and 1st chakras. this is usually information that has to do with survival and personal power. gut feelings will be activated when we all of a sudden feel like we shouldn't go to that party or down that dark alley.Â  this is a feeling not a knowingness or vision. we generally can feel a tightness in our tummies. to activate our gut feelings, we need to tap into our 3rd and 1st chakras.

womb feelings/womb intuition- this comes from our 2nd chakra and our female womb space (the energetic space around the female organs). this is an ancient aching type feeling that gives us information about where we have come from, where we need to go, how to care for ourselves and others, as well as how to uncover and heal our deepest emotions. often we hold other... continued in comments.

text:
if you feel the world is moving too slowly, it probably is. there is too big a difference between the top and the bottom of society. even accepting that there is a top and bottom of society is a problem.

but some days, for a moment, feeling deep gratitude for the place we are in, for how far we have come and for those who have fought so hard and so smart for us is enough.

thank you rbg - for your voice. let's hope our sons and daughters do more and accept less.

#oscar2018 hollywood's biggest night took time to deliver a timely message and celebrate diversity in filmmaking; 
ashley judd, salma hayek and annabella sciorra â€” three women who publicly accused harvey weinstein of sexual misconduct â€” took the stage together to introduce the segment.

when jimmy kimmel kicked off this year's oscars, he promised a 
ight of positivity" during his opening monologue. during the third act of sunday's show, that promise materialized when the academy devoted a segment to honoring the #metoo and time's up movements and highlighted the diversity in movie-making in the last year. "many spoke their truth and the journey ahead is long, but slowly a new path has emerged," said judd, referencing the women and men who have come forward to say #metoo and time's up. those voices have joined together to create a "mighty chorus," she added. judd shared a hope that the next 90 years of the academy awards will "empower these limitless possibilities of equality, diversity inclusivity, intersectionality â€” that's what this year has promised us." hayek then introduced a pre-taped segment highlighting some of this year's most diverse and ground-breaking filmmakers â€” from greta gerwig and dee rees to @ava duvernay and kumail nanjiani â€” whom she referred to as "unstoppable spirits who kicked ass and broke through bias perceptions against their gender racer and ethnicity to tell their stories." jimmy kimmel said "we need to set an example and if we can work together here to stop sexual harassment in the workplace, women will only have to deal with harassment all the time, at every other place they go." perhaps speaking to critics of hollywood award shows who believe they have grown "too political," kimmel explained that the night's show would include brave and outspoken voices of the #metoo, #timesup and #neveragain movements in hopes of spurring positive change."this is a night for positivity," he declared before rattling off all the names of nominees who had the potential to break or set new

some spiritual reflections & resources on this beautiful day:

one of my favorite questions that stumps some christians and makes others smile is, â€œif god is all powerful, all knowing and all that, why is there so much injustice and suffering in the world? iâ€™m sure this is a thought thatâ€™s crossed everyoneâ€™s mind at least once, it certainly has mine.

on my central park west walk from 59th columbus circle to 84th st. this is what i see. homeless people taking refuge on church steps, expensive statues that only remind me of white supremacy n colonization, and one of the most polarizing yet most human claims of our generation: #blacklivesmatter.

i donâ€™t have any answers, except that as a history student, the history of humanity is full of inequality, greed, innovation, art, war, celebrations and funerals -
death and new life.

jesus had work to do when his feet journeyed on soil of the roman empire, iâ€™m no better than him so i too have work to do while my feet journey on soil of
the united states of empire.

whatever you believe in, if love is at the core iâ€™m sure you can understand that hate is unsustainable and love conquers all. like water love makes up a majority of our bodies, brains, diets, and cleanses. may love shower you and overwhelm your heart so that you may remember in these perilous times, like a child with fairytales memorized, that love conquers all.

sankofa, ubuntu, i love you.
fear. psalm 37

text:
gop is dead. gop remains dead. and we have killed him. how shall we comfort ourselves, the murderers of all murderers? what was holiest and mightiest of all that the world has yet owned has bled to death under our knives: who will wipe this blood off us? what water is there for us to clean ourselves? what festivals of atonement, what sacred games shall we have to invent? is not the greatness of this deed too great for us? must we ourselves not become gods simply to appear worthy of it?

howlindsey doody

text:
there's a brand new dance
but i don't know its name
that people from bad homes
do again and again
it's big and it's bland
full of tension and fear
they do it over there but we don't do it here

fashion! turn to the left
fashion! turn to the right
oooh, fashion!
we are the goon squad
and we're coming to town
beep-beep
beep-beep

listen to me - don't listen to me
talk to me - don't talk to me
dance with me - don't dance with me, no
beep-beep

there's a brand new talk
but it's not very clear
that people from good homes
are talking this year
it's loud and tasteless
and i've heard it before
you shout it while you're dancing
on the whole dance floor
oh bop, fashion

fashion! turn to the left
fashion! turn to the right
oooh, fashion!
we are the goon squad
and we're coming to town
beep-beep
beep-beep

listen to me - don't listen to me
talk to me - don't talk to me
dance with me - don't dance with me, no
beep-beep

oh, bop, do do do do do do do do
fa-fa-fa-fa-fashion
oh, bop, do do do do do do do do
fa-fa-fa-fa-fashion
la-la la la la la la-la

david bowie

â£â£
still floating from all the incredible souls i met yesterday which felt like a beautiful convergence of my personal and professional worlds- unpacking the nuances of sexual violence recovery in such a supportive community. â£â£
â£â£
i am eternally grateful for your passion and for sharing your hearts with me. thank you for those who traveled hours to be with us and for the virtual connections that turned into in-person hugs. â£â£
â£â£
one of the conference organizerâ€™s grandmother was in attendance and she sat in the middle of the room and smiled at me the entire speech. she was such a safe anchor for me when i felt nervous. thank you to the amazing + warm mindfulness in human development research team at duke and unc for inviting me and for showing me the meaning of genuine hospitality! and the most overwhelming thank you to my sister @almina_k who traveled from dc to support and be with me. even just 24 hours with you refills my spirit. thank you for a day iâ€™ll never forget. â¤ï¸â£
â£
this rumi quote reminds me so beautifully of the way my passion for my work has unfolded:â£
â£
â€œlet yourself be silently drawn by the strange pull of what you really love. it will not lead you astray.â€â£
â£
see you in 2 weeks st. louis! ğŸ™ğŸ½ #traumainformedyoga #embodiedlearningsummit

text:
i'll write again

in awe of the bird that echoes through the both of us,
of the flow of winds and the untouched stardust,

of a silence that is too loud,
of love that nature endowed.

i'll write again

but i don't open my eyes to this serenity yet,
they open in chaos, unpredictability, in threat.

when the only choice is between black or white
they open to flag bearers of peace fumbling for the grays in moments of injustice,

there could be so much more to see and despite 
they open to the free hands of predators & their accomplice.

i'll write again 
my eyes cannot close to this until your eyes open
and see it is just through this pen that i am coping

don't let them distract you when they bark, "keep the personal away from the political" 
it is only through the personal you can feel this unentitled pain, this forced upon shame, the blood thumping in my veins that scribbles: this could all be political.

i'll write again 
of how we walked through the fire hand in hand,
of how, in our way, now no one stands.

of what i chose to believe 
of my last sigh of relief.
