text:
i just received this photo from my @yogaofrecovery teacher, durga leela, & it has me in tears with so much #gratitude  i didn't know it at the time, but this first #blessing from @swamisitaramananda was the beginning of a life that i had never imagined ğŸ˜…
*
this first photo is my first ashram experience @sivanandayogafarm in the depth of my #addiction to opiates almost 5 years ago. i am ashamed to i can even see the fresh scars on the side of my face. *
5 years later i can tell you that a becoming a #yogaofrecoverycounselor & integrating it's principles in my life does these things for me:
*
1. helps me stay #cleanandsober #onedayatatime for over 3.5 years,like many of us, i didn't get it perfect right away #progressnotperfection ğŸ™
*
2. off of all opiate replacement therapies after 1 year of recovery #suboxone that western doctors lie & say we need for life!
*
3. quit all other addictions like #cigarettes #rockstar #shoppingaddiction #dramaqueen
*
4. true & lasting #ptsdrecovery from my own #metoo experience that lead me to my #drugofchoice in the first place
*
5. i love every #moment of life today & the people i meet around the world.  now i get to learn to bring this same #love & #healing that was so freely given to me,  to everyone i come in contact with. *
thank you @yogaofrecovery & @swamisitaramananda for giving me a life of recovery beyond my wildest dreams. 
#caligirlinindia #photooftheday #yogaeverydamnday #sivanandabahamas #sober #sobriety

text:
last day to view @rosemarymezadesplasâ€™s jane anger on view at #56bogart
jane anger features hand-sewn human hair drawings, watercolors and onsite installations. rosemary meza-desplasâ€™ figurative artworks emphasize line and movement. the title refers to a 16th century pamphlet published in england titled jane anger, her protection for women.

meza-desplas explores the concept of anger as a tool for change by juxtaposing found imagery from social media, art history and mass media. she is interested in how the social movements, womenâ€™s marches and #metoo, harnessed anger in order to forefront an array of gender-based burdens. 
this exhibition includes meza-desplasâ€™ most recent drawings which incorporate her gray hair. she has been sewing with her own hair since 2000. her hair is hand-sewn into a variety of grounds with small embroidery needles. meza-desplasâ€™ decision to collect, sort and utilize hair as a vehicle for art-making is informed by socio-cultural symbolism, feminism and body issues, and religious symbolism. hair embodies a dichotomy: it can be sexy and engaging to people, on the other hand, it can be repulsive â€“ like a hair in your soup or a hair on your hotel pillow. 
there are religious connotations to hair which coincide with symbolism reflecting strength, sensuality and reverence; such as delila cutting off samsonâ€™s hair and mary magdalen washing the feet of jesus with her hair.

text:
the lotus is such a symbol of beauty, yet it doesnâ€™t start out as pure and pristine as itâ€™s usually shown. it is born in deep waters where it is rooted in mud and muck, surrounded by fish and insects, rough conditions at every turn. it is literally born in conditions no one would choose!

despite these conditions, the lotus flower holds strong, pushing aside each of these dirty obstacles as it makes its way to clearer surfaces above. the stem continues to grow, and the pod slowly surfaces above the water into the clean air, finally freeing itself from confines of the mucky water. 
it is then that the lotus slowly opens each beautiful petal to the sun, basking in the world now surrounding it. it is ready to take on the world! despite being born into dark, murky conditions, where hope for such beautiful life seems dubious, the lotus grows, rises above adversity. 
you might feel like a lotus flower that hasnâ€™t yet reached the surface where itâ€™s easier to breathe, stretch and see the sun. i truly believe it is your time to turn the mess youâ€™ve lived with into a message, the darkness youâ€™ve felt into light to guide the way for others, your pain has purpose.

reach out for support *

text: listening to this album as an adult is pretty eye-opening. when i was young, i just thought #tlc was cool, pretty, crazysexycool, fun, cool rappers and cartoony. but they sang about the #metoo movement before #metoo was #metoo (on his story: â€œhis story will be his story and my story is a waste of timeâ€). about examining the quality of your friendships (on what about your friends: â€œwill they stand their ground? will they let you down again?â€). when most rnb groups were singing about heartbreak and the virtues of their vaginas, tlc challenged our views on pop music, hip hop, sexiness and feminism with their music. sometimes the lyrics are a bit short sighted and immature (and their image is.... questionable) but they were teenagers when they first perfomed/wrote these. people tend to celebrate #crazysexycool and #fanmail (rightfully so) but oooooh on the tlc tip was a strong debut and really set the foundation. #tboz #lefteye #chilli

text:
this week i was invited to moderate a panel called â€œdigital activism comes of age: how youth have used technology to challenge mainstream media.â€
.
i sat next to thought leaders and community leaders to discuss the notion of clicktivism, digital action, or â€œslactivismâ€ as itâ€™s sometimes called. though it has itâ€™s critics, itâ€™s seen as providing all the personal satisfaction of aiding a cause, with little effort or understanding given to actually addressing and solving the underlying problem.
.
mediums like twitter and instagram are being used by young people to amplify their concerns, demand authentic storytelling, and create a dialogue that may eventually dispel stereotypes. mobile phones with video-sharing capabilities, accompanied by ubiquitous social media use, has led to widespread movements like #blacklivesmatter, #metoo, and #neveragain, that have moved beyond short term viral sensations in the digital space to sustained impact in the public sphere.
.
within this particular clip, one person within the audience asked the question of how she could improve diversity and inclusion and build community within her organization.
.
my response? it works both ways from a macro and micro level. from a large organizational standpoint (macro), we must make an effort in caring about things that are on the hearts and mind of people of color. we must empower those around us to tell their own story and to share their perspective. we must hire diverse representation to be decision influencers and makers within the room. from an individual standpoint (micro), sometimes policies and mindsets within large corporations can take a significant amount of time to change, so we must not wait for people to pick us, but instead we must pick ourselves to be the change we want to see in this world. we donâ€™t necessarily have to wait for an invitation to have a seat at the table. start building your own table of community around your concerns and shared experiences. your community is worth something. it canâ€™t be sold. itâ€™s built with trust, consistency and time. community is the new currency.
.
thank you to @bestpracticemedia and @ktippyy for inviting to me to contribute my voice.

text:
#twft52 week 8 â€“ swipe for starter questions and my own response (also at link in profile). âœ’ğŸ–¤
@thewordforthis
â€¢
the word for this is â€œhurt.â€
â€¢
this is my nature: nurtured
to stand guard, every cell
trained to misfire, to tire my
atoms, exhaust each bond, bones
shattered, scattered, vigilant force
aimed toward exhumed
enemy ghosts, armies long dismantled, dust and stone; white hot light from
distant stars that imploded long
before i was born, searing
me still.
â€¢
as usual, iâ€™m writing with no forethought and little editing. and as usual, what emerged wasnâ€™t what i expected from the word. fibromyalgia, the vicious phantom pain of it, the crushing fatigue, the connections i finally broke open (the number of practitioners who paused delicately, held my gaze for an extra beat as they asked whether there was any history of ongoing abuse or trauma, the passive phrasing not lost on me).
â€¢
the grandfather, drafted (i think?) into the us presence in the korean war, serving in a role that required little intellect or fortitude, another early emphasis of his powerlessness.
â€¢
an echo of cemeteries, funerals or headstone unveilings for one distant elder or another, at which he would sob the loss of his own parents, dragging me into the sweaty, rank crook of his armpit as he forced his grief on me (my god, why did no one ever attempt to release me?), his arm damp, clamped around my neck, his tears and saliva and snot pooling where my hair parted.
â€¢
i would use the visualization technique a teacher once taught me, when iâ€™d mentioned insomnia: picture yourself, the bed, the room, the house, the street, the town, the city, the country, the earth, the solar system, the milky way, the universe. slowly zoom out, until youâ€™re not even there, and youâ€™ll drift off.
â€¢
the thing is, i *am* still here. itâ€™s all still here, etched into places so small i have to reverse the process, zoom in, the lens growing stronger each time, find a tool fine enough to buff these pathways smooth again.

text:
happy oscar sunday! new @hollywoodandbeyondshow with @stevenjbrittingham podcast featuring andrea evans and minh collins is now available. two amazing guests discussing their powerful new documentary:

the topic is one that no longer can be denied, ignored or swept under the rug. sexual harassment. jobs for sexual favors. even rape. the casting couch is about to get rocked. 
my special guests andrea evans (one life to live / @boldandbeautifulcbs) and director minh collins have a lot to say about their new documentary film â€˜rocking the couchâ€™. we discuss the situation that has plagued hollywood and so many other industries on the next episode.

text: we keep talking about church leaders and members who have sexually abused children because sadly, there is no shortage of these stories! parents are being groomed right along with their children at alarming rates and we have to stop and acknowledge that this is due in part to our unwillingness to admit that everyone in church does not have good intentions. the scriptures spoke of those who would come in and take advantage of church goers and cause serious harm. this article speaks of how the pastor not only sexual assaulted a member of his church, but he had an accomplice in his wife, and he perverted scripture and his position to keep the child silent and compliant. parents, be on guard! these predacious characters are looking for vulnerabilities to exploit to gain access to your child. church is a common locale for predators to search for victims because people are so welcoming and extend trust so easily based on what they believe is a shared desire to please god and do right by others. this is just not so and until we acknowledge this and change our behaviors and attitudes towards those we interact with in the church, abuse will continue.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #church #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #socialmedia

text:
"last april, a female reporter from tv asahi accused junichi fukuda, the top bureaucrat at the finance ministry, of sexual harassment.

the woman recorded the conversation, excerpts of which were later published by weekly magazine shukan shincho.

the magazine also released an edited audio clip said to be of fukuda telling the woman: â€œcan i touch your breast?â€ â€œshould we have an affair when the budget is enacted?â€ and â€œi will tie your hands.â€ fukuda initially denied the allegations but resigned after other media outlets jumped on the story and his position became untenable.

the above case is just one example of increasing efforts being made by women in japan to speak out against sexual harassment and violence." --- for the entire article:

https://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2019/02/23/national/history/defining-heisei-era-women-japan-speak-inequality/#.xhkpsknolik

text:
neurology retraction for 'racist characterizations'â£â €
â£â €
an editor of neurology, the flagship journal of the aan, has resigned following the swift retraction last week of an article because it contained what the editor admitted were "racist characterizations."â£â €
â£â €
"the error has compelled us to seriously re-examine our editorial processes, informed by conversations with a number of diversity leaders within the aan," editor-in chief robert a. gross, md, wrote. â£â €
â£â €
as medscape medical news previously reported, the now-retracted essay, "lucky and the root doctor," described "reggie, a 60-year-old black man referred because of muscle weakness and suspected inflammatory myopathy." â£â €
â£â €
it said that reggie's wife was "a roly-poly woman" whose "abundant rolls of fat jiggled as she giggled."â£â €
â£â €
the author of the article, william w. campbell, md, msha, an emeritus professor at the uniformed services university of health sciences and a retired colonel in the us army, told medscape medical news last week that he did not mean to offend anyone.â£â €
â£â €
in addition to immediately suspending the journal's humanities section, the publication "will require that any paper that focuses on a group of people (for example, racial treatment disparities in stroke care) will have a member of that group, or a content expert on that group, or both, who will assure that the handling editor will have an appropriate range of opinion on which to base decisions..."â£â €
â£â €
â£â €
more on this unfortunate situation by tapping the bio link.â£â €
â£â €
â£â €
we'd also like to hear from you. have you ever experienced or witnessed any bias or disparities in your medical career? please tell us about it in the comments. â£â €

i struggled with this for a long time and in so many different waysâ€”each of those ways stalled my own healing and progress.  regardless of what abuse someone suffered through, it doesnâ€™t give them the right to turn that pain on you.  as survivors we sometimes justify the abuse weâ€™ve suffered because we are aware of the abuse our perpetrators endured as well.  that mindset completely blocks our own healing.  learning to forgive our abusers is different than justifying that abuse. forgiving sets us free, while justifying the abuse keeps us trapped in pain.

text: "grief is the turning point of healing, but we resist it because our minds create judgments around it. we might feel that itâ€™s weak or that we are over it. we might resist being sad due to early internalized messages of "donâ€™t cry," or we might feel like our grief is uncomfortable for others. until we can see grieving the loss of experiences we missed out on due to our own survival adaptations as necessary for transforming our relationship to vulnerability (both physiological, mental and emotional), we will stay in the feedback loop of stress. like a record album with a scratch, no matter how we might wish it to move forward, without the wash of grief our bodies will just continue to skip back to the place it startedâ€”fear." #recovery #resilience #yoga #women #selflove #selfhelp #timbo #trauma #traumarecovery #mindfulness #metoo #men #healing #wellbeing #community #connection #vulnerability

text:
i'll write again

in awe of the bird that echoes through the both of us,
of the flow of winds and the untouched stardust,

of a silence that is too loud,
of love that nature has endowed.

i'll write again

but i don't open my eyes to this serenity yet,
they open in chaos, unpredictability, in threat.

when the only choice is between black or white
they open to flag bearers of peace fumbling for the grays in moments of injustice,

there could be so much more to see and despite 
they open to the free hands of predators & their accomplice.

i'll write again 
my eyes cannot close to this until your eyes open
and see it is just through this pen that i am coping

don't let them distract you when they bark, "keep the personal away from the political" 
it is only through the personal you can feel this unentitled pain, this forced upon shame, the blood thumping in my veins that whispers: this could all be political.

i'll write again 
of how we walked through the fire hand in hand,
of how, in our way, now no one stands.

of what i chose to believe 
of my last sigh of relief.

so if you decide to stay in yesterday, or even if you did go kick it somewhere, get and head to this event! i promise you wonâ€™t be disappointed at all! the sisters' safety and self- defense symposium, presented by @afrikanmartialarts and @iyalogun ojetade is designed for women of african descent, ages 11-adult.

in this highly intensive gathering of women, who are experts in the fields of security, risk assessment, self-defense, crisis management and conflict resolution, you will learn:
situational awareness
avoiding violence
identifying danger signals
assertiveness and verbal self-defense
the warrior's mindset
escapes from common grabs, holds and chokes
basic techniques to get back to your feet after falling or being knocked down
improvised weapons

the purpose of the symposium is to teach and empower sisters to percent, interrupt, heal from, and neutralize violence and abuse. 
just $45.00 for the entire day at the door.
$40.00 in advance (send to cashapp:$balogunojetade). #sistersteachingsisters
#notavictim #atlbrunch #metoo #atlanta #selfdefense #martialarts #selfcare #atl

â€˜to be a manâ€™: a portrait series challenging the concept of toxic masculinity.
.
sushrut. nepal. "itâ€™s okay for me to wear make-up. being a straight man affords me the privilege of being comfortable. because, as a man, i sit at the very center of the system that creates the dominant narratives about the world, i can always feel comfortable that my act of self expression is valid. however, people who donâ€™t identify as straight men donâ€™t have the same luxury. the very act of self expression can be fraught with inconveniences. so it is important for me that i use my relative position of privilege to highlight ways in which non-traditional modes of expression are equally valid. presenting myself in traditionally feminine ways is a way for me to assert that healthy masculinity allows a space for expressions that are as varied as the people who make them."
